<br>
I think this article sums up our position. It's exactly the kind of story I wish I could write. I recommend everyone read through it. Some great information and he actually uses the word 'fearmongers'. It's from Time magazine and although its dated last April its a good example of what we are trying to put across. Not that we have to focus on nuclear spacecraft. Commercial nuclear power is probably our major theme for the page. I'm thinking of doing a piece on the &quot;myth of proliferation control&quot;. I've always held the view that a nuclear club can't keep everyone out of its clubhouse forever. Recent events don't persuade me I should rethink this opinion. Long before Sept 11 I already knew the real threat to be terrorists. Not an original idea, Ted Taylor was convinced of it back in the 60's. While we ban ourselves from researching nuclear weapons, other groups are buying or swapping technology which will allow them to catch up and perhaps even overtake us. In the past, any nation that ignored a technology has always suffered for it later on. When England virtually banned cars at the turn of the century, they left themselves out of the massive car manufacturing trade and were never really able to ever catch up with the rest of Europe again. England also ignored the submarine as a potentially deadly naval vessel. Much to the joy of Germany who used Uboats to great effect. England could not see how it might develop. It's a mistake we keep repeating. Any technology we throw away becomes a niche for someone else to develop at leasure. Banning leading edge science like cloning, genetic engineering, nanotechnology or nukes simply because of fear is irational and self damaging. The consequences of standing still as the rest of the World keeps moving forward is far more frightening than the technology itself. With understanding comes familiarity and answers. The answer to any threat never came from sticking your head in the sand. Answers always lie close to the problems requiring them. By better comprehending the nature of nuclear weapons, we can perhaps better find solutions to them being used in aggression.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A> at: 11/21/02 6:25:49 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 44<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/21/02 8:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pro-nuclear thread.</span><hr size=1> Well, what will be a littile hard to convince the greens, but if we can get the public on our side, they won't matter. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brp17>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 166<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/21/02 9:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pro-nuclear thread.</span><hr size=1> That is a very good article, the type of think I want to include in the newsletter. Unfortunatly being a student I can only subscribe to so many kinds of newsletters, still, very interesting. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard